of the research and its potential impact.\n\n10. **References:**\n    - Include any relevant references that support the research proposal.\n    - Ensure that all references are properly cited.\n\n### Example Draft Structure\n\n#### Introduction and Background\n- **Abstract:** Brief summary of the research.\n- **Problem Setting:** Description of the problem and its significance.\n- **Current State of the Field:** Overview of existing research and identified gaps.\n\n#### Research Questions\n- **Q1:** How can we enhance the noise resilience of reward signals from vision-language models in autonomous robot navigation and manipulation systems to improve task execution accuracy and reliability?\n- **Q2:** Why is it important to enhance noise resilience in reward signals for autonomous robots?\n- **Q3:** What are the technical challenges in developing noise-resilient reward functions?\n- **Q4:** Why hasn't the issue of noise resilience in reward signals been fully addressed in previous research?\n- **Q5:** What are the key components of the proposed approach and what are the expected outcomes?\n\n#### Objectives\n- **Objective 1:** Develop advanced noise-resilient reward functions.\n- **Objective 2:** Integrate multimodal data to improve decision-making.\n- **Objective 3:** Implement a reinforcement learning-based plan validation and correction mechanism.\n- **Objective 4:** Evaluate the system using comprehensive metrics.\n\n#### Methodology\n- **Noise-Resilient Reward Functions:** Utilize advanced algorithms like BiMI and adaptive filtering techniques.\n- **Multimodal Data Integration:** Develop a data fusion framework and integrate visual and tactile feedback.\n- **Plan Validation and Correction:** Implement reinforcement learning-based mechanisms and use historical data for training.\n\n#### Evaluation Metrics\n- **Recovery Rate (RR) and Success Rate (SR):** Use these metrics to evaluate the performance of the improved system.\n- **Additional Metrics:** Introduce additional metrics such as task completion time and error rate to provide a comprehensive evaluation.\n\n#### Expected Outcomes\n- **Outcome 1:** Enhanced reliability and robustness of COME-robot.\n- **Outcome 2:** Improved task execution and reduced failures in real-world environments.\n\n#### Timeline\n- **Month 1-2:** Literature review and initial setup.\n- **Month 3-4:** Development of noise-resilient reward functions.\n- **Month 5-6:** Integration of multimodal data.\n- **Month 7-8:** Implementation of plan validation and correction mechanisms.\n- **Month 9-10:** Evaluation and testing.\n- **Month 11-12:** Final report and dissemination.\n\n#### Resources and Tools\n- **Hardware:** Real robot, sensors, and computing resources.\n- **Software:** GPT-4V, reinforcement learning frameworks, data fusion tools.\n\n#### Conclusion\n- **Summary:** Recap of the research proposal.\n- **Impact:** Discussion of the potential impact on the field of autonomous robotics.\n\n#### References\n- **Citations:** List of relevant references.\n\nBy following this structured approach, you can create a comprehensive and persuasive research proposal that addresses the identified gaps and contributes to the field of autonomous robotics.", 'agent2': 'The next task after refining the \'5q\' and drafting the initial proposal document is to **seek feedback** from peers or mentors. This step is crucial to ensure that the proposal is robust, addresses the key challenges effectively, and is well-articulated. Here’s a detailed plan for this next step:\n\n### Step 3: Seek Feedback\n\n1. **Identify Feedback Providers:**\n   - **Peers:** Colleagues or fellow researchers who have expertise in autonomous robotics, vision-language models, or related fields.\n   - **Mentors:** Advisors or senior researchers who can provide guidance and constructive criticism.\n   - **External Experts:** If possible, include feedback from experts outside your immediate network to gain diverse perspectives.\n\n2. **Prepare the Proposal:**\n   - Ensure that the draft proposal is complete and well-organized.\n   - Highlight the key sections, especially the \'5q\' format, to make it easier for reviewers to provide specific feedback.\n\n3. **Share the Proposal:**\n   - Use appropriate channels to share the proposal, such as email, collaborative documents (e.g., Google Docs), or research forums.\n   - Provide a brief introduction to the proposal and the specific areas where feedback is most needed.\n\n4. **Request Specific Feedback:**\n   - Ask reviewers to focus on specific aspects of the proposal, such as the clarity of the research questions, the methodology, the expected results, and the potential impact.\n   - Encourage them to provide both positive feedback and constructive criticism.\n\n5. **Set a Deadline:**\n   - Provide a reasonable deadline for feedback to ensure timely responses.\n   - Be flexible and open to extending the deadline if necessary.\n\n6. **Collect Feedback:**\n   - Gather all feedback in a structured manner, noting comments and suggestions from each reviewer.\n   - Categorize feedback into themes or areas for improvement.\n\n7. **Incorporate Feedback:**\n   - Review the collected feedback and identify common themes or critical issues.\n   - Make necessary revisions to the proposal based on the feedback.\n   - Ensure that all significant comments are addressed and incorporated into the final draft.\n\n8. **Iterate if Necessary:**\n   - If the feedback indicates major issues or areas for improvement, consider revising the proposal and seeking additional feedback.\n   - Repeat the feedback loop as needed to refine the proposal further.\n\n### Example of Feedback Request\n\n**Subject:** Request for Feedback on Research Proposal - Enhancing the COME-Robot Framework\n\n**Dear [Reviewer\'s Name],**\n\nI hope this email finds you well. I am currently working on a research proposal titled "Enhancing the COME-Robot Framework for Robust Autonomous Navigation and Manipulation." The proposal aims to address specific challenges in object detection, verification, and replanning within the COME-robot framework.\n\nI would greatly appreciate your feedback on the draft proposal. Your insights will be invaluable in ensuring that the research questions are well-defined, the methodology is robust, and the expected results are realistic.\n\nPlease find the draft attached. I would be particularly interested in your thoughts on the following sections:\n- **Research Questions (5q):** Are the research questions clear and well-articulated?\n- **Methodology:** Are the proposed methods feasible and well-explained?\n- **Expected Results:** Are the expected outcomes realistic and achievable?\n- **Potential Impact:** How does this research contribute to the field of autonomous robotics?\n\nYour feedback is due by [Deadline]. Please feel free to share your comments via email or directly in the document.\n\nThank you very much for your time and assistance.\n\nBest regards,  \n[Your Name]  \n[Your Contact Information]\n\nBy following these steps, you can ensure that the research proposal is well-received and refined, setting a strong foundation for your research project.', 'agent3': 'The next task is to refine and finalize the research proposal based on feedback and ensure that it is well-structured, coherent, and clearly communicates the research objectives, methodology, and expected outcomes. Here are the steps to take:\n\n1. **Review and Revise:**\n   - Review the proposal for clarity, coherence, and logical flow.\n   - Ensure that each section (Introduction, Problem Statement, Significance and Importance, Challenges and Complexity, Previous Work and Gaps, Proposed Approach, Expected Results, Timeline, and Integration of NLP Expertise) is well-defined and contributes to the overall narrative.\n\n2. **Seek Feedback:**\n   - Share the draft with peers, mentors, or colleagues who have expertise in both NLP and robotics.\n   - Incorporate their feedback to improve the proposal.\n\n3. **Finalize the Proposal:**\n   - Address any comments or suggestions received.\n   - Ensure that the proposal is polished and ready for submission or presentation.\n\n4. **Prepare for Presentation:**\n   - Create a presentation deck that summarizes the key points of the proposal.\n   - Prepare to discuss the proposal in detail, addressing potential questions or concerns.\n\n5. **Submit or Present:**\n   - If the proposal is for a grant, conference, or academic journal, follow the submission guidelines.\n   - If the proposal is for an internal review or presentation, schedule a meeting to present the proposal.\n\nHere is a checklist to ensure all aspects are covered:\n\n- **Introduction:** Clearly states the research field and its importance.\n- **Problem Statement:** Clearly defines the specific research question.\n- **Significance and Importance:** Explains the broader implications and impact.\n- **Challenges and Complexity:** Identifies and discusses the challenges.\n- **Previous Work and Gaps:** Reviews existing research and identifies gaps.\n- **Proposed Approach:** Details the methodology, including datasets and metrics.\n- **Expected Results:** Outlines the expected outcomes.\n- **Timeline:** Provides a realistic schedule.\n- **Integration of NLP Expertise:** Demonstrates how NLP techniques will be applied.\n\nBy following these steps, you can ensure that your research proposal is comprehensive, well-structured, and effectively communicates your research vision and goals.'}, 'task_results': [{'agent1': "Result from the model:To draft the detailed research proposal based on the refined research questions and enhanced methodology, I will follow the structured approach outlined in the task. Here is the detailed draft:\n\n### Introduction and Background\n#### Abstract\nThis research aims to enhance the reliability and robustness of COME-robot, an autonomous robot navigation and manipulation system, by addressing the challenges in noise resilience of reward signals from vision-language models (VLMs). The proposed approach includes developing advanced noise-resilient reward functions, integrating multimodal data, and implementing a reinforcement learning-based plan validation and correction mechanism.\n\n#### Problem Setting\nThe problem setting revolves around the development of COME-robot, which uses GPT-4V for reasoning and adaptive planning in open-ended real-world scenarios. The system is designed to actively perceive the environment, perform situated reasoning, and recover from failures through a combination of action primitives and multimodal reasoning. However, the performance of COME-robot is affected by noise in reward signals from VLMs, leading to errors in task execution.\n\n#### Current State of the Field\nPrevious research has focused on individual components of the robot's reasoning and planning capabilities but has not fully addressed the issue of noise resilience in reward signals. Existing solutions may lack the necessary integration of multimodal data and advanced noise-resilient algorithms. This research aims to bridge these gaps by developing a comprehensive approach.\n\n### Research Questions\n1. **Q1:** How can we enhance the noise resilience of reward signals from vision-language models in autonomous robot navigation and manipulation systems to improve task execution accuracy and reliability?\n2. **Q2:** Why is it important to enhance noise resilience in reward signals for autonomous robots?\n3. **Q3:** What are the technical challenges in developing noise-resilient reward functions?\n4. **Q4:** Why hasn't the issue of noise resilience in reward signals been fully addressed in previous research?\n5. **Q5:** What are the key components of the proposed approach and what are the expected outcomes?\n\n### Objectives\n1. **Objective 1:** Develop advanced noise-resilient reward functions.\n2. **Objective 2:** Integrate multimodal data to improve decision-making.\n3. **Objective 3:** Implement a reinforcement learning-based plan validation and correction mechanism.\n4. **Objective 4:** Evaluate the system using comprehensive metrics.\n\n### Methodology\n#### Noise-Resilient Reward Functions\n- **Techniques:** Utilize advanced algorithms such as BiMI (Binary Mutual Information) to mitigate noise in reward signals from VLMs.\n- **Adaptive Filtering:** Implement adaptive filtering techniques to dynamically adjust reward signals based on real-time feedback.\n\n#### Multimodal Data Integration\n- **Data Fusion Framework:** Develop a data fusion framework that integrates information from multiple sensors (visual and tactile) to enhance decision-making.\n- **Sensor Integration:** Combine visual and tactile feedback to improve the accuracy of reward signals.\n\n#### Plan Validation and Correction\n- **Reinforcement Learning Techniques:** Implement a reinforcement learning-based plan validation and correction mechanism.\n- **Historical Data Training:** Use historical data to train the system to recognize and correct common planning errors.\n\n### Evaluation Metrics\n- **Recovery Rate (RR) and Success Rate (SR):** Use these metrics to evaluate the performance of the improved system.\n- **Additional Metrics:** Introduce additional metrics such as task completion time and error rate to provide a comprehensive evaluation.\n\n### Expected Outcomes\n- **Outcome 1:** Enhanced reliability and robustness of COME-robot.\n- **Outcome 2:** Improved task execution and reduced failures in real-world environments.\n\n### Timeline\n- **Month 1-2:** Literature review and initial setup.\n- **Month 3-4:** Development of noise-resilient reward functions.\n- **Month 5-6:** Integration of multimodal data.\n- **Month 7-8:** Implementation of plan validation and correction mechanisms.\n- **Month 9-10:** Evaluation and testing.\n- **Month 11-12:** Final report and dissemination.\n\n### Resources and Tools\n- **Hardware:** Real robot, sensors, and computing resources.\n- **Software:** GPT-4V, reinforcement learning frameworks, data fusion tools.\n\n### Conclusion\n- **Summary:** Recap of the research proposal.\n- **Impact:** Discussion of the potential impact on the field of autonomous robotics.\n\n### References\n- **Citations:** List of relevant references.\n\nThis structured approach ensures that the research proposal is well-rounded, feasible, and impactful.\n"}, {'agent2': 'Result from the model:To proceed with seeking feedback on the draft proposal, I will follow the detailed plan outlined. Here’s how I will execute Step 3: Seek Feedback:\n\n### Step 3: Seek Feedback\n\n1. **Identify Feedback Providers:**\n   - **Peers:** Colleagues or fellow researchers who have expertise in autonomous robotics, vision-language models, or related fields.\n   - **Mentors:** Advisors or senior researchers who can provide guidance and constructive criticism.\n   - **External Experts:** If possible, include feedback from experts outside your immediate network to gain diverse perspectives.\n\n2. **Prepare the Proposal:**\n   - Ensure that the draft proposal is complete and well-organized.\n   - Highlight the key sections, especially the \'5q\' format, to make it easier for reviewers to provide specific feedback.\n\n3. **Share the Proposal:**\n   - Use appropriate channels to share the proposal, such as email, collaborative documents (e.g., Google Docs), or research forums.\n   - Provide a brief introduction to the proposal and the specific areas where feedback is most needed.\n\n4. **Request Specific Feedback:**\n   - Ask reviewers to focus on specific aspects of the proposal, such as the clarity of the research questions, the methodology, the expected results, and the potential impact.\n   - Encourage them to provide both positive feedback and constructive criticism.\n\n5. **Set a Deadline:**\n   - Provide a reasonable deadline for feedback to ensure timely responses.\n   - Be flexible and open to extending the deadline if necessary.\n\n6. **Collect Feedback:**\n   - Gather all feedback in a structured manner, noting comments and suggestions from each reviewer.\n   - Categorize feedback into themes or areas for improvement.\n\n7. **Incorporate Feedback:**\n   - Review the collected feedback and identify common themes or critical issues.\n   - Make necessary revisions to the proposal based on the feedback.\n   - Ensure that all significant comments are addressed and incorporated into the final draft.\n\n8. **Iterate if Necessary:**\n   - If the feedback indicates major issues or areas for improvement, consider revising the proposal and seeking additional feedback.\n   - Repeat the feedback loop as needed to refine the proposal further.\n\n### Example of Feedback Request\n\n**Subject:** Request for Feedback on Research Proposal - Enhancing the COME-Robot Framework\n\n**Dear [Reviewer\'s Name],**\n\nI hope this email finds you well. I am currently working on a research proposal titled "Enhancing the COME-Robot Framework for Robust Autonomous Navigation and Manipulation." The proposal aims to address specific challenges in object detection, verification, and replanning within the COME-robot framework.\n\nI would greatly appreciate your feedback on the draft proposal. Your insights will be invaluable in ensuring that the research questions are well-defined, the methodology is robust, and the expected results are realistic.\n\nPlease find the draft attached. I would be particularly interested in your thoughts on the following sections:\n- **Research Questions (5q):** Are the research questions clear and well-articulated?\n- **Methodology:** Are the proposed methods feasible and well-explained?\n- **Expected Results:** Are the expected outcomes realistic and achievable?\n- **Potential Impact:** How does this research contribute to the field of autonomous robotics?\n\nYour feedback is due by [Deadline]. Please feel free to share your comments via email or directly in the document.\n\nThank you very much for your time and assistance.\n\nBest regards,  \n[Your Name]  \n[Your Contact Information]\n\n### Execution Plan\n\n1. **Identify Feedback Providers:**\n   - Peers: [List of peers]\n   - Mentors: [List of mentors]\n   - External Experts: [List of external experts]\n\n2. **Prepare the Proposal:**\n   - Ensure the draft is complete and well-organized.\n   - Highlight the \'5q\' format.\n\n3. **Share the Proposal:**\n   - Use email and Google Docs to share the proposal.\n   - Provide a brief introduction and specify areas needing feedback.\n\n4. **Request Specific Feedback:**\n   - Ask reviewers to focus on research questions, methodology, expected results, and potential impact.\n   - Encourage both positive and constructive feedback.\n\n5. **Set a Deadline:**\n   - Set a deadline of [Date].\n\n6. **Collect Feedback:**\n   - Gather feedback in a structured manner.\n   - Categorize feedback into themes.\n\n7. **Incorporate Feedback:**\n   - Review feedback and identify common themes.\n   - Make necessary revisions.\n\n8. **Iterate if Necessary:**\n   - Revise and seek additional feedback if needed.\n\nBy following these steps, I will ensure that the research proposal is well-received and refined, setting a strong foundation for the research project.\n\n### Next Steps\n\n- Identify and contact feedback providers.\n- Share the draft proposal via email and Google Docs.\n- Set a deadline for feedback.\n- Collect and categorize feedback.\n- Incorporate feedback into the proposal.\n- Iterate if necessary.\n\nThis plan will help me effectively seek and incorporate feedback, ensuring the proposal is robust and well-articulated.\n'}, {'agent3': 'Result from the model:To refine and finalize the research proposal based on feedback and ensure it is well-structured, coherent, and clearly communicates the research objectives, methodology, and expected outcomes, I will follow the outlined steps. Here is the detailed plan:\n\n### Step-by-Step Plan\n\n1. **Review and Revise:**\n   - Review the proposal for clarity, coherence, and logical flow.\n   - Ensure that each section (Introduction, Problem Statement, Significance and Importance, Challenges and Complexity, Previous Work and Gaps, Proposed Approach, Expected Results, Timeline, and Integration of NLP Expertise) is well-defined and contributes to the overall narrative.\n\n2. **Seek Feedback:**\n   - Share the draft with peers, mentors, or colleagues who have expertise in both NLP and robotics.\n   - Incorporate their feedback to improve the proposal.\n\n3. **Finalize the Proposal:**\n   - Address any comments or suggestions received.\n   - Ensure that the proposal is polished and ready for submission or presentation.\n\n4. **Prepare for Presentation:**\n   - Create a presentation deck that summarizes the key points of the proposal.\n   - Prepare to discuss the proposal in detail, addressing potential questions or concerns.\n\n5. **Submit or Present:**\n   - If the proposal is for a grant, conference, or academic journal, follow the submission guidelines.\n   - If the proposal is for an internal review or presentation, schedule a meeting to present the proposal.\n\n### Checklist\n\n- **Introduction:** Clearly states the research field and its importance.\n- **Problem Statement:** Clearly defines the specific research question.\n- **Significance and Importance:** Explains the broader implications and impact.\n- **Challenges and Complexity:** Identifies and discusses the challenges.\n- **Previous Work and Gaps:** Reviews existing research and identifies gaps.\n- **Proposed Approach:** Details the methodology, including datasets and metrics.\n- **Expected Results:** Outlines the expected outcomes.\n- **Timeline:** Provides a realistic schedule.\n- **Integration of NLP Expertise:** Demonstrates how NLP techniques will be applied.\n\n### Draft Proposal\n\n#### 1. Introduction\n\nThe field of autonomous robot navigation and manipulation in open environments is rapidly advancing, with a focus on integrating advanced AI models like GPT-4V for reasoning and adaptive planning. However, current systems still face significant challenges in object detection, grasping, plan verification, and visual analysis, which can lead to task failures and reduced reliability. Additionally, there is a need to address biases in these systems and ensure they perform well across diverse and low-resource settings.\n\n#### 2. Problem Statement\n\nWhat are the key challenges in object detection, grasping, plan verification, and visual analysis that lead to task failures in autonomous robot systems like COME-robot, and how can these challenges be addressed to ensure fairness and robustness across diverse and low-resource environments?\n\n**Challenges:**\n- **Detection Errors:** COME-robot struggles with missed and wrong detections, which can lead to task failures.\n- **Execution Failures:** Incorrect plans or invalid API calls can cause execution failures, particularly in grasping tasks.\n- **Verification Process:** The verification step for detected objects is error-prone and can lead to incorrect predictions.\n- **Visual Analysis Issues:** Blurred images or inherent VLM issues can cause misjudgments in task completion.\n\n#### 3. Significance and Importance\n\nAddressing these challenges is crucial for improving the reliability and robustness of autonomous robot systems, enabling them to perform complex tasks accurately and efficiently in real-world environments. Solving these problems will have significant implications for the development of more advanced and practical AI-driven robots. Additionally, ensuring fairness and robustness across diverse and low-resource settings will make these systems more equitable and accessible.\n\n#### 4. Challenges and Complexity\n\nThe challenges in object detection, grasping, plan verification, and visual analysis are complex and multifaceted. Naive or straightforward approaches may fail due to the inherent uncertainties and variability in real-world environments. Technical, theoretical, and practical obstacles include the need for advanced neural networks, sophisticated algorithms, and robust verification systems. Addressing bias and ensuring performance across diverse and low-resource settings adds another layer of complexity.\n\n#### 5. Previous Work and Gaps\n\nPrevious research has focused on individual components of the problem, such as object detection or grasping, but has not addressed the integrated challenges faced by autonomous robot systems. Existing solutions often lack the adaptability and robustness required for real-world applications, and there is a need for more comprehensive approaches. Additionally, the integration of fairness and robustness across diverse and low-resource settings is a relatively new and challenging area.\n\n#### 6. Proposed Approach\n\nThe proposed approach involves developing a multi-faceted system that integrates advanced object detection, grasping, plan verification, and visual analysis techniques, with a focus on fairness and robustness across diverse and low-resource environments. Key components include:\n\n- **Enhanced Object Detection:**\n  - Use ensemble methods and advanced neural networks to improve detection accuracy.\n  - Incorporate fairness considerations by developing a debiasing layer that corrects errors in projected annotations, achieving state-of-the-art results in low-resource settings.\n\n- **Improved Grasping:**\n  - Design a sophisticated grasping algorithm that considers robot position and orientation, with a focus on bias mitigation.\n  - Leverage syntactic structures in coreference resolution to enhance grasping accuracy.\n\n- **Advanced Plan Verification:**\n  - Create a plan verification system using reinforcement learning to check plan feasibility, ensuring fairness and robustness.\n  - Develop probabilistic methods for machine translation quality estimation to emphasize the significance of uncertainty in predictions.\n\n- **Visual Analysis Enhancements:**\n  - Develop methods to enhance image quality and handle occlusions, with a focus on low-resource settings.\n  - Implement a system to handle occlusions and partial object views more effectively, leveraging neural networks for superior performance on benchmark datasets.\n\n- **Adaptive Replanning Strategies:**\n  - Design adaptive algorithms to quickly recover from failures and generate new plans with minimal delay.\n  - Use machine learning techniques to predict and mitigate potential failures before they occur.\n\n#### 7. Expected Results\n\nExpected outcomes include a more reliable and robust autonomous robot system that can perform complex tasks accurately and efficiently in real-world environments. The system will be evaluated through comprehensive experiments on a real robot, showcasing improved performance metrics such as success rates, recovery rates, and execution times.\n\n#### 8. Timeline\n\n- **Month 1-2:** Literature review and problem definition.\n- **Month 3-4:** Development of enhanced object detection and verification systems.\n- **Month 5-6:** Design and implementation of improved grasping algorithms.\n- **Month 7-8:** Creation of advanced plan verification systems.\n- **Month 9-10:** Development of visual analysis enhancements.\n- **Month 11-12:** Design and implementation of adaptive replanning strategies.\n- **Month 13-14:** Comprehensive experiments and evaluation.\n- **Month 15:** Final report and dissemination of results.\n\n#### 9. Integration of NLP Expertise\n\n- **Low-Resource Languages:** Develop a debiasing layer that corrects errors in projected annotations, achieving state-of-the-art results in low-resource settings.\n- **Model Bias:** Incorporate fairness considerations in object detection, grasping, and plan verification.\n- **Language Understanding:** Leverage syntactic structures in coreference resolution to enhance grasping accuracy and develop probabilistic methods for machine translation quality estimation.\n\n### Next Steps\n\n1. **R